======================================================================
  PART 2: ALGEBRAIC ANALYSIS
======================================================================

H = I(CG, 2) where CG = odd-cycle conflict graph
I(G, x) = Σ_{k≥0} i_k x^k

H mod 7 = I(CG, 2) mod 7

If we could show I(G, 2) ≡ 0 (mod 7) is impossible
for ALL odd-cycle conflict graphs, this would prove it.

Note: I(G, 2) ≡ 0 (mod 7) ≡ I(G, 2) ≡ 0 (mod 7)
And 2³ ≡ 1 (mod 7), so the evaluation at 2 mod 7
uses a cube root of unity in F_7.

In F_7: 2³ = 8 ≡ 1, so 2 is a primitive 3rd root of unity.
Let ω = 2 in F_7. Then ω³ = 1, ω ≠ 1.
The minimal polynomial of ω over F_7 is x² + x + 1
(since ω²+ω+1 = 4+2+1 = 7 ≡ 0 mod 7).

OBSERVATION: I(G, ω) = 0 in F_7 means the independence polynomial
has ω as a root modulo 7.
Since ω satisfies ω²+ω+1 = 0, this means
(x²+x+1) | I(G, x) in F_7[x].

CLAIM: For odd-cycle conflict graphs of tournaments,
(x²+x+1) never divides I(G, x) mod 7.

