======================================================================
  PART 4: I(CG,x) MOD (x²+x+1) OVER F_7
======================================================================

Since 2 is a root of x²+x+1 over F_7,
H ≡ 0 (mod 7) iff (x²+x+1) | I(CG,x) (mod 7).

Question: does I(CG,x) ≡ 0 (mod x²+x+1) ever happen?

n=6: checking I(CG,2) mod 7 for all 32768 tournaments...
  H ≡ 0 (mod 7): 0/32768 tournaments (6.3s)

n=7: sampling 3000 tournaments for H mod 7...
  trial 0: 0.0s
  trial 1000: 0.5s
  trial 2000: 1.0s
  H ≡ 0 (mod 7): 322/3000 tournaments
  BROKEN! 322 tournaments have H ≡ 0 (mod 7).

======================================================================
  PART 5: THE 5-7 CONNECTION
======================================================================

Why are 5 and 7 special for forbidden residues?

5 = the discriminant of the Fibonacci recurrence
7 = 2³ - 1, a Mersenne prime
  Also: 7 = the first prime where ord_p(2) < p-1
  (ord_7(2) = 3, not 6)

The key: powers of 2 mod 7 cycle with period 3,
making 2 a CUBE ROOT OF UNITY in F_7.
So H = I(CG, 2) mod 7 evaluates at a special algebraic point.

In F_7: x²+x+1 = (x-2)(x-4)
  Check: (2)²+2+1 = 7 ≡ 0 ✓
  Check: (4)²+4+1 = 21 ≡ 0 ✓

So H ≡ 0 (mod 7) iff I(CG, 2) ≡ 0 in F_7
iff the cyclotomic polynomial Φ_3(x) = x²+x+1 divides I(CG,x) in F_7[x]

EQUIVALENTLY: H ≡ 0 (mod 7) iff BOTH I(CG,2) ≡ 0 AND I(CG,4) ≡ 0 (mod 7)
But we already know I(CG,2) = H and I(CG,4) is a different evaluation.

At n=5, I(CG,4) mod 7 distribution:
  I(CG, 4) mod 7: {0: 280, 1: 120, 2: 240, 3: 240, 4: 24, 5: 120}
  I(CG, 4) ≡ 0 (mod 7): 280 tournaments

======================================================================
  PART 6: CONJECTURE — H ≢ 0 (mod 7) FOR ALL n
======================================================================

Evidence so far:
  n=3: H ∈ {1,3} → H mod 7 ∈ {1,3} ✓ (no 0)
  n=4: H ∈ {1,3,5} → H mod 7 ∈ {1,3,5} ✓
  n=5: verified all 1024 ✓
  n=6: verified all 32768 ✓
  n=7: sampled 3000, found 322

The conjecture FAILS at n=7!
So H ≡ 0 (mod 7) first becomes possible at some n between 7 and beyond.

